# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: secure-headers
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] OWASP considers the term cross-site scripting to be a misnomer.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] It initially was an attack that was used for breaching data across sites, but gradually started to include other forms of data injection attacks.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Security on the web depends on a variety of mechanisms, including an underlying concept of trust known as the same-origin policy.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Content from URLs where any of these three attributes are different will have to be granted permissions separately.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Cross-site scripting attacks use known vulnerabilities in web-based applications, their servers, or the plug-in systems on which they rely.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Exploiting one of these, attackers fold malicious content into the content being delivered from the compromised site.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] When the resulting combined content arrives at the client-side web browser, it has all been delivered from the trusted source, and thus operates under the permissions granted to that system.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] By finding ways of injecting malicious scripts into web pages, an attacker can gain elevated access-privileges to sensitive page content, to session cookies, and to a variety of other information maintained by the browser on behalf of the user.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Cross-site scripting attacks are a case of code injection.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Microsoft security-engineers introduced the term "cross-site scripting" in January 2000.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] The definition gradually expanded to encompass other modes of code injection, including persistent and non-JavaScript vectors (including ActiveX, Java, VBScript, Flash, or even HTML scripts), causing some confusion to newcomers to the field of information security.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] XSS vulnerabilities have been reported and exploited since the 1990s.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Prominent sites affected in the past include the social-networking sites Twitter and Facebook.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Cross-site scripting flaws have since surpassed buffer overflows to become the most common publicly reported security vulnerability, with some researchers in 2007 estimating as many as 68% of websites are likely open to XSS attacks.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] There is no single, standardized classification of cross-site scripting flaws, but most experts distinguish between at least two primary flavors of XSS flaws: *non-persistent* and *persistent*.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Some sources further divide these two groups into *traditional* (caused by server-side code flaws) and *DOM-based* (in client-side code).
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] The *non-persistent* (or *reflected*) cross-site scripting vulnerability is by far the most basic type of web vulnerability.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] These holes show up when the data provided by a web client, most commonly in HTTP query parameters (e.g.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] HTML form submission), is used immediately by server-side scripts to parse and display a page of results for that user, without properly sanitizing the content.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Because HTML documents have a flat, serial structure that mixes control statements, formatting, and the actual content, any non-validated user-supplied data included in the resulting page without proper HTML encoding, may lead to markup injection.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] A classic example of a potential vector is a site search engine: if one searches for a string, the search string will typically be redisplayed verbatim on the result page to indicate what was searched for.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] If this response does not properly escape or reject HTML control characters, a cross-site scripting flaw will ensue.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] A reflected attack is typically delivered via email or a neutral web site.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] The bait is an innocent-looking URL, pointing to a trusted site but containing the XSS vector.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] If the trusted site is vulnerable to the vector, clicking the link can cause the victim's browser to execute the injected script.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] A classic example of this is with online message boards where users are allowed to post HTML formatted messages for other users to read.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] For example, suppose there is a dating website where members scan the profiles of other members to see if they look interesting.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] For privacy reasons, this site hides everybody's real name and email.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] The only time a member's real name and email are in the browser is when the member is signed in, and they can't see anyone else's.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Suppose that Mallory, an attacker, joins the site and wants to figure out the real names of the people she sees on the site.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] To do so, she writes a script designed to run from other users' browsers when *they* visit *her* profile.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] The script then sends a quick message to her own server, which collects this information.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] To do this, for the question "Describe your Ideal First Date", Mallory gives a short answer (to appear normal), but the text at the end of her answer is her script to steal names and emails.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] If the script is enclosed inside a `<script>` element, it won't be shown on the screen.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Then suppose that Bob, a member of the dating site, reaches Mallory's profile, which has her answer to the First Date question.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Her script is run automatically by the browser and steals a copy of Bob's real name and email directly from his own machine.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Persistent XSS vulnerabilities can be more significant than other types because an attacker's malicious script is rendered automatically, without the need to individually target victims or lure them to a third-party website.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Particularly in the case of social networking sites, the code would be further designed to self-propagate across accounts, creating a type of client-side worm.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] The methods of injection can vary a great deal; in some cases, the attacker may not even need to directly interact with the web functionality itself to exploit such a hole.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Any data received by the web application (via email, system logs, IM etc.) that can be controlled by an attacker could become an injection vector.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] XSS vulnerabilities were originally found in applications that performed all data processing on the server side.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] User input (including an XSS vector) would be sent to the server, and then sent back to the user as a web page.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] The need for an improved user experience resulted in popularity of applications that had a majority of the presentation logic (maybe written in JavaScript) working on the client-side that pulled data, on-demand, from the server using AJAX.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] As the JavaScript code was also processing user input and rendering it in the web page content, a new sub-class of reflected XSS attacks started to appear that was called *DOM-based cross-site scripting*.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] In a DOM-based XSS attack, the malicious data does not touch the web server.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Rather, it is being reflected by the JavaScript code, fully on the client side.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] An example of a DOM-based XSS vulnerability is the bug found in 2011 in a number of jQuery plugins.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Prevention strategies for DOM-based XSS attacks include very similar measures to traditional XSS prevention strategies but implemented in JavaScript code and contained in web pages (i.e. input validation and escaping).
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Some JavaScript frameworks have built-in countermeasures against this and other types of attack — for example AngularJS.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Self-XSS is a form of XSS vulnerability that relies on social engineering in order to trick the victim into executing malicious JavaScript code in their browser.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Although it is technically not a true XSS vulnerability due to the fact it relies on socially engineering a user into executing code rather than a flaw in the affected website allowing an attacker to do so, it still poses the same risks as a regular XSS vulnerability if properly executed.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Mutated XSS happens when the attacker injects something that is seemingly safe but is rewritten and modified by the browser while parsing the markup.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] This makes it extremely hard to detect or sanitize within the website's application logic.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] An example is rebalancing unclosed quotation marks or even adding quotation marks to unquoted values in CSS font-family properties.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] There are several escaping schemes that can be used depending on where the untrusted string needs to be placed within an HTML document including HTML entity encoding, JavaScript escaping, CSS escaping, and URL (or percent) encoding.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Most web applications that do not need to accept rich data can use escaping to largely eliminate the risk of XSS attacks in a fairly straightforward manner.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Performing HTML entity encoding only on the five XML significant characters is not always sufficient to prevent many forms of XSS attacks, security encoding libraries are usually easier to use.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Some web template systems understand the structure of the HTML they produce and automatically pick an appropriate encoder.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Many operators of particular web applications (e.g. forums and webmail) allow users to utilize HTML markup.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] When accepting HTML input from users (say, `<b>very</b> large`), output encoding (such as `&lt;b&gt;very&lt;/b&gt; large`) will not suffice since the user input needs to be rendered as HTML by the browser (so it shows as `**very** large`, instead of `<b>very</b> large`).
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Stopping an XSS attack when accepting HTML input from users is much more complex in this situation.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Often, untrusted HTML input must be run through an HTML sanitization engine to ensure that it does not contain potentially malicious JavaScript code.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Many validations rely on parsing out (blacklisting) specific "at risk" HTML tags such as the `<iframe>`, `<link>`, and `<script>` tag, or by only allowing certain tags and removing or escaping others.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Another popular method is to strip user input of " and ' however this can also be bypassed as the payload can be concealed with obfuscation.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Besides content filtering, other imperfect methods for cross-site scripting mitigation are also commonly used.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] One example is the use of additional security controls when handling cookie-based user authentication.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Many web applications rely on session cookies for authentication between individual HTTP requests, and because client-side scripts generally have access to these cookies, simple XSS exploits can steal these cookies.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] To mitigate this particular threat (though not the XSS problem in general), many web applications tie session cookies to the IP address of the user who originally logged in, then only permit that IP to use that cookie.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] This is effective in most situations (if an attacker is only after the cookie), but obviously breaks down in situations where an attacker is behind the same NATed IP address or web proxy as the victim, or the victim is changing his or her mobile IP.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Another mitigation present in Internet Explorer (since version 6), Firefox (since version 2.0.0.5), Safari (since version 4), Opera (since version 9.5) and Google Chrome, is an *HttpOnly* flag which allows a web server to set a cookie that is unavailable to client-side scripts.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] While beneficial, the feature can neither fully prevent cookie theft nor prevent attacks within the browser.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] While Web 2.0 and Ajax developers require the use of JavaScript, some web applications are written to allow operation without the need for any client-side scripts.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] This allows users, if they choose, to disable scripting in their browsers before using the application.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] In this way, even potentially malicious client-side scripts could be inserted unescaped on a page, and users would not be susceptible to XSS attacks.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Some browsers or browser plugins can be configured to disable client-side scripts on a per-domain basis.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] This approach is of limited value if scripting is allowed by default, since it blocks bad sites only *after* the user knows that they are bad, which is too late.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Functionality that blocks all scripting and external inclusions by default and then allows the user to enable it on a per-domain basis is more effective.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] This has been possible for a long time in Internet Explorer (since version 4) by setting up its so called "Security Zones", and in Opera (since version 9) using its "Site Specific Preferences".
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] A solution for Firefox and other Gecko-based browsers is the open source NoScript add-on which, in addition to the ability to enable scripts on a per-domain basis, provides some XSS protection even when scripts are enabled.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Another problem with script blocking is that many users do not understand it, and do not know how to properly secure their browsers.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Yet another drawback is that many sites do not work without client-side scripting, forcing users to disable protection for that site and opening their systems to vulnerabilities.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] The Firefox NoScript extension enables users to allow scripts selectively from a given page while disallowing others on the same page.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] For example, scripts from example.com could be allowed, while scripts from advertisingagency.com that are attempting to run on the same page could be disallowed.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Trusted types changes Web APIs to check that values have been trademarked as trusted.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] As long as programs only trademark trustworthy values, an attacker who controls a JavaScript string value cannot cause XSS.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Trusted types are designed to be auditable by blue teams.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] Another defense approach is to use automated tools that will remove XSS malicious code in web pages, these tools use static analysis and/or pattern matching methods to identify malicious codes potentially and secure them using methods like escaping.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] When a cookie is set with the `SameSite=Strict` parameter, it is stripped from all cross-origin requests.
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] When set with `SameSite=Lax`, it is stripped from all non-"safe" cross-origin requests (that is, requests other than GET, OPTIONS, and TRACE which have read-only semantics).
[src:secure-headers/cross-site-scripting] The feature is implemented in Google Chrome since version 63 and Firefox since version 60.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] HTTP is a request–response protocol in the client–server model.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] A transaction starts with a client submitting a request to the server, the server attempts to satisfy the request and returns a response to the client that describes the disposition of the request and optionally contains a requested resource such as an HTML document or other content.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] In a common scenario, a web browser acts as the client, and a web server, hosting one or more websites, is the server.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] A web browser is an example of a user agent (UA).
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Other types of user agent include the indexing software used by search providers (web crawlers), voice browsers, mobile apps, and other software that accesses, consumes, or displays web content.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] HTTP is designed to permit intermediate network elements to improve or enable communications between clients and servers.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] High-traffic websites often benefit from web cache servers that deliver content on behalf of upstream servers to improve response time.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Web browsers cache previously accessed web resources and reuse them, whenever possible, to reduce network traffic.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] HTTP proxy servers at private network boundaries can facilitate communication for clients without a globally routable address, by relaying messages with external servers.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] To allow intermediate HTTP nodes (proxy servers, web caches, etc.) to accomplish their functions, some of the HTTP headers (found in HTTP requests/responses) are managed hop-by-hop whereas other HTTP headers are managed end-to-end (managed only by the source client and by the target web server).
[src:secure-headers/http-header] A web resource is located by a uniform resource locator (URL), using the Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) schemes *http* and *https*.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] URIs are encoded as hyperlinks in HTML documents, so as to form interlinked hypertext documents.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The protocol has been revised over time.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] A version is identified as HTTP/# where # is the version number.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] This article covers aspects of all versions but provides primary coverage for HTTP/0.9, HTTP/1.0, and HTTP/1.1.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Separate articles cover HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 in detail.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] In HTTP/1.0, a separate TCP connection to the same server is made for every resource request.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] In HTTP/1.1, instead a TCP connection can be reused to make multiple resource requests (i.e. of HTML pages, frames, images, scripts, stylesheets, etc.).
[src:secure-headers/http-header] HTTP/1.1 communications therefore experience less latency as the establishment of TCP connections presents considerable overhead, especially under high traffic conditions.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Enhancements added with HTTP/2 allow for less latency and, in most cases, higher speeds than HTTP/1.1 communications.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] HTTP/3 uses QUIC + UDP transport protocols instead of TCP.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Only the IP layer is used (which UDP, like TCP, builds on).
[src:secure-headers/http-header] This slightly improves the average speed of communications and avoids the occasional problem of TCP connection congestion that can temporarily block or slow down the data flow of all its streams (another form of "*head of line blocking*").
[src:secure-headers/http-header] HTTP/2 is supported by 71% of websites (34.1% HTTP/2 + 36.9% HTTP/3 with backwards compatibility) and supported by almost all web browsers (over 98% of users).
[src:secure-headers/http-header] It is also supported by major web servers over Transport Layer Security (TLS) using an Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation (ALPN) extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] HTTP/3 is used on 36.9% of websites and is supported by most web browsers, i.e.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] (at least partially) supported by 97% of users.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] HTTP/3 uses QUIC instead of TCP for the underlying transport protocol.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Like HTTP/2, it does not obsolete previous major versions of the protocol.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] In 2019, support for HTTP/3 was first added to Cloudflare and Chrome and also enabled in Firefox.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] HTTP/3 has lower latency for real-world web pages and loads faster than HTTP/2, in some cases over three times faster than HTTP/1.1, which is still commonly the only protocol enabled.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] HTTPS, the secure variant of HTTP, is used by more than 85% of websites.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] HTTP presumes an underlying and reliable transport layer protocol.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The standard choice of the underlying protocol prior to HTTP/3 is Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:secure-headers/http-header] HTTP/3 uses a different transport layer called QUIC, which provides reliability on top of the unreliable User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:secure-headers/http-header] HTTP/1.1 and earlier have been adapted to be used over plain unreliable UDP in multicast and unicast situations, forming HTTPMU and HTTPU.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] They are used in UPnP and Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP), two protocols usually run on a local area network.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] HTTP is a stateless application-level protocol and it requires a reliable network transport connection to exchange data between client and server.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] In HTTP implementations, TCP/IP connections are used using well-known ports (typically port 80 if the connection is unencrypted or port 443 if the connection is encrypted, see also List of TCP and UDP port numbers).
[src:secure-headers/http-header] In HTTP/2, a TCP/IP connection plus multiple protocol channels are used.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] In HTTP/3, the application transport protocol QUIC over UDP is used.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Data is exchanged through a sequence of request–response messages which are exchanged by a session layer transport connection.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] An HTTP client initially tries to establish a connection, real or virtual, with a server.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] An HTTP server listening on the port accepts the connection and then waits for a client's request message.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The client sends its HTTP request message.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Upon receiving the request the server sends back an HTTP response message, which includes header(s) plus a body if it is required.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The body of this response message is typically the requested resource, although an error message or other information may also be returned.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] At any time and for many reasons, either the client or server can close the connection.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Closing a connection is usually advertised by one or more HTTP headers in the last request or response.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] In HTTP/0.9, the TCP/IP connection is always closed after server response has been sent, so it is never persistent.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] In HTTP/1.0, the TCP/IP connection should always be closed by server after a response has been sent.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] In HTTP/1.1, a keep-alive-mechanism was officially introduced so that a connection could be reused for more than one request/response.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Such persistent connections reduce request latency perceptibly because the client does not need to re-negotiate the TCP 3-Way-Handshake connection after the first request has been sent.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Another positive side effect is that, in general, the connection becomes faster with time due to TCP's slow-start-mechanism.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] HTTP/1.1 added also HTTP pipelining in order to further reduce lag time when using persistent connections by allowing clients to send multiple requests before waiting for each response.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Because of this, only HEAD and some GET requests (i.e. limited to real file requests and so with URLs without query string used as a command, etc.) could be pipelined in a safe and idempotent mode.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] After many years of struggling with the problems introduced by enabling pipelining, this feature was first disabled and then removed from most browsers.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Pipelining was also removed because of the announced adoption of HTTP/2.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] HTTP/2 extended the usage of persistent connections by multiplexing many concurrent requests/responses through a single TCP/IP connection.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] HTTP/3 does not use TCP/IP connections but QUIC + UDP.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] In HTTP/0.9, a requested resource was always sent in its entirety.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] HTTP/1.0 added headers to manage resources cached by a client in order to allow conditional GET requests.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] As a stateless protocol, HTTP does not require the web server to retain information or status about each user for the duration of multiple requests.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] If a web application needs an application session, it implements it via HTTP cookies, hidden variables in a web form or another mechanism.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Typically, to start a session, an interactive login is performed, and to end a session, a logout is requested by the user.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] These kind of operations use a custom authentication mechanism, not HTTP authentication.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] HTTP provides multiple authentication schemes such as basic access authentication and digest access authentication which operate via a challenge–response mechanism whereby the server identifies and issues a challenge before serving the requested content.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] HTTP provides a general framework for access control and authentication, via an extensible set of challenge–response authentication schemes, which can be used by a server to challenge a client request and by a client to provide authentication information.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The authentication mechanisms described above belong to the HTTP protocol and are managed by client and server HTTP software (if configured to require authentication before allowing client access to one or more web resources), and not by the web applications using an application session.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The HTTP authentication specification includes realms that provide an arbitrary, implementation-specific construct for further dividing resources common to a given root URI.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The realm value string, if present, is combined with the canonical root URI to form the protection space component of the challenge.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] This in effect allows the server to define separate authentication scopes under one root URI.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The most popular way of establishing an encrypted HTTP connection is HTTPS.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Two other methods for establishing an encrypted HTTP connection also exist: Secure Hypertext Transfer Protocol, and using the HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header to specify an upgrade to TLS.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Browser support for these two is, however, nearly non-existent.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] This section describes messages for HTTP/1.1.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Later versions, HTTP/2 and HTTP/3, use a binary protocol, where headers are encoded in a single `HEADERS` and zero or more `CONTINUATION` frames using HPACK (HTTP/2) or QPACK (HTTP/3), which both provide efficient header compression.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The request or response line from HTTP/1 has also been replaced by several pseudo-header fields, each beginning with a colon (`:`).
[src:secure-headers/http-header] At the highest level, a message consists of a header followed by a body.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] A header consists of lines of ASCII text; each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Structured data that differs for request vs. response.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] lines (at least 1 for HTTP/1.1); see below.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] A body consists of data in any format; not limited to ASCII.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The format must match that specified by the `Content-Type` header field if the message contains one.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] A body is optional or, in other words, can be blank.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Before HTTP/2, the term *entity* was used to mean the body plus header fields that describe the body.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] In particular, not all headers were considered part of the entity.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The term *entity header* referred to a header that was considered part of the entity, and sometimes the body was called the *entity body*.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Modern documentation uses *body* and *header* without using *entity*.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] A header field represents metadata about the containing message.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Generally, the information of a header field is used by software and not shown to the user.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] A header field line is formatted as a name-value pair with a colon separator.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Whitespace is not allowed around the name, but leading and trailing whitespace is ignored for the value part.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Unlike a method name that must match exactly (case-sensitive), a header field name is matched ignoring case although often shown with each word capitalized.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] For example, the following are header fields for `Host` and `Accept-Language`.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The standards do not limit the size of a header field or the number of fields in a message.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] However, most servers, clients, and proxy software impose limits for practical and security reasons.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] For example, the Apache 2.3 server by default limits the size of each field to 8190 bytes, and there can be at most 100 header fields in a single request.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Although deprecated by RFC 7230, in the past, long lines could be split into multiple lines with a continuation line starting with a space or tab character.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] A request is sent by a client to a server.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The start line includes a method name, a request URI and the protocol version with a single space between each field.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Request header fields allow the client to pass additional information beyond the request line, acting as request modifiers (similarly to the parameters of a procedure).
[src:secure-headers/http-header] They give information about the client, about the target resource, or about the expected handling of the request.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] In the HTTP/1.1 protocol, all header fields except `Host` are optional.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] A request line containing only the path name is accepted by servers to maintain compatibility with HTTP clients before the HTTP/1.0 specification in RFC 1945.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The protocol structures transaction as operating on resources.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] What a resource represents, whether pre-existing data or data that is generated dynamically, depends on the implementation of the server.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Often, the resource corresponds to a file or the output of an executable running on the server.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] A request identifies a method (sometimes informally called *verb*) to classify the desired action to be performed on a resource.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The HTTP/1.0 specification defined the GET, HEAD, and POST methods as well as listing the PUT, DELETE, LINK and UNLINK methods under additional methods.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] However, the HTTP/1.1 specification added five new methods: PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, and TRACE.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Any client can use any method and the server can be configured to support any combination of methods.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] If a method is unknown to an intermediate, it will be treated as an unsafe and non-idempotent method.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] There is no limit to the number of methods that can be defined, which allows for future methods to be specified without breaking existing infrastructure.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] For example, WebDAV defined seven new methods and RFC 5789 specified the PATCH method.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] A general-purpose web server is required to implement at least GET and HEAD, and all other methods are considered optional by the specification.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] This is in contrast to HTTP header field names which are case-insensitive.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The request is for a representation of a resource.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] include the representation data in the body.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] in the response header, without having to transfer the entire representation.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The request is to process a resource in some way.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The request is to create or update a resource with the state in the request.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] A distinction from POST is that the client specifies the target location on the server.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] to the origin server identified by the request target.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Request is for a report of the HTTP methods that are supported for a resource.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] This can be used to check the functionality of a web server by requesting '*' instead of a specific resource.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Requests the server to respond with the received request in the response body.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] That way a client can see what (if any) changes or additions have been made by intermediaries.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The request is to modify a resource according to its partial state in the request.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Compared to PUT, this can save bandwidth by sending only part of a resource's representation instead of all of it.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] A request method is *safe* if a request with that method has no intended effect on the server.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The methods GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, and TRACE are defined as safe.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] In other words, safe methods are intended to be read-only.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Safe methods can still have side effects not seen by the client, such as appending request information to a log file or charging an advertising account.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] In contrast, the methods POST, PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, and PATCH are not safe.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] They may modify the state of the server or have other effects such as sending an email.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Such methods are therefore not usually used by conforming web robots or web crawlers; some that do not conform tend to make requests without regard to context or consequences.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Despite the prescribed safety of GET requests, in practice their handling by the server is not technically limited in any way.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Careless or deliberately irregular programming can allow GET requests to cause non-trivial changes on the server.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] This is discouraged because of the problems which can occur when web caching, search engines, and other automated agents make unintended changes on the server.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] For example, a website might allow deletion of a resource through a URL such as *https://example.com/article/1234/delete*, which, if arbitrarily fetched, even using GET, would simply delete the article.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] A properly coded website would require a DELETE or POST method for this action, which non-malicious bots would not make.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] One example of this occurring in practice was during the short-lived Google Web Accelerator beta, which prefetched arbitrary URLs on the page a user was viewing, causing records to be automatically altered or deleted *en masse*.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The beta was suspended only weeks after its first release, following widespread criticism.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] A request method is *idempotent* if multiple identical requests with that method have the same effect as a single such request.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The methods PUT and DELETE, and safe methods are defined as idempotent.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Safe methods are trivially idempotent, since they are intended to have no effect on the server whatsoever; the PUT and DELETE methods, meanwhile, are idempotent since successive identical requests will be ignored.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] A website might, for instance, set up a PUT endpoint to modify a user's recorded email address.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] If this endpoint is configured correctly, any requests which ask to change a user's email address to the same email address which is already recorded—e.g. duplicate requests following a successful request—will have no effect.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Similarly, a request to DELETE a certain user will have no effect if that user has already been deleted.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] In contrast, the methods POST, CONNECT, and PATCH are not necessarily idempotent, and therefore sending an identical POST request multiple times may further modify the state of the server or have further effects, such as sending multiple emails.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] In some cases this is the desired effect, but in other cases it may occur accidentally.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] A user might, for example, inadvertently send multiple POST requests by clicking a button again if they were not given clear feedback that the first click was being processed.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] While web browsers may show alert dialog boxes to warn users in some cases where reloading a page may re-submit a POST request, it is generally up to the web application to handle cases where a POST request should not be submitted more than once.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Note that whether or not a method is idempotent is not enforced by the protocol or web server.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] It is perfectly possible to write a web application in which (for example) a database insert or other non-idempotent action is triggered by a GET or other request.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] To do so against recommendations, however, may result in undesirable consequences, if a user agent assumes that repeating the same request is safe when it is not.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] A request method is *cacheable* if responses to requests with that method may be stored for future reuse.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The methods GET, HEAD, and POST are defined as cacheable.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] In contrast, the methods PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, TRACE, and PATCH are not cacheable.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] A response is sent to the client by the server.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The start line of a response consists of the protocol version, a status code and optionally a reason phrase with fields separated by a single space character.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The following response start line specifies protocol version `HTTP/1.1`, status code `400` and reason phrase `Bad Request`.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Response header fields allow the server to pass additional information beyond the status line, acting as response modifiers.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] They give information about the server or about further access to the target resource or related resources.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Each response header field has a defined meaning which can be further refined by the semantics of the request method or response status code.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The status code is a three-digit, decimal, integer value that represents the disposition of the server's attempt to satisfy the client's request.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Generally, a client handles a response primarily based on the status code and secondarily on response header fields.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] A client may not understand each status code that a server reports but it must understand the class as indicated by the first digit and treat an unrecognized code as equivalent to the x00 code of that class.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The request was received, continuing process.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The request was successfully received, understood, and accepted.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Further action needs to be taken in order to complete the request.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The request cannot be fulfilled due to an issue that the client might be able to control.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The server failed to fulfill an apparently valid request.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The standard reason phrases are only recommendations.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] A web server is allowed to use a localized equivalent.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] If a status code indicates a problem, the user agent might display the reason phrase to the user to provide further information about the nature of the problem.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The standard also allows the user agent to attempt to interpret the reason phrase, though this might be unwise since the standard explicitly specifies that status codes are machine-readable and reason phrases are human-readable.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The following demonstrates an HTTP/1.1 request-response transaction for a server at www.example.com, port 80.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] HTTP/1.0 would use the same messages except for a few missing headers.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 would use the same request-response mechanism but with different representations for HTTP headers.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The following is a request with no body.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] It consists of a start line, 6 header fields and a blank line – each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The `Host` header field distinguishes between various DNS names sharing a single IP address, allowing name-based virtual hosting.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] While optional in HTTP/1.0, it is mandatory in HTTP/1.1.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Although not clear in the representation above (due to limitations of this wiki), the blank line at the end results in ending in two line terminator sequences.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Represented as a stream of characters, a shorted version of above shows this more clearly with `<CRLF>` representing a line terminator sequence: `GET / HTTP/1.1<CRLF>Host: www.example.com<CRLF><CRLF>`.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] In the following response, the ETag (entity tag) header field is used to determine if a cached version of the requested resource is identical to the current version of the resource on the server.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The `Content-Type` header field specifies the Internet media type of the data conveyed by the HTTP message, and `Content-Length` indicates its length in bytes.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The HTTP/1.1 webserver publishes its ability to respond to requests for a byte range of the resource by including `Accept-Ranges: bytes`.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] This is useful, if the client needs to have only certain portions of a resource sent by the server, which is called byte serving.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] When `Connection: close` is sent, it means that the web server will close the TCP connection immediately after the end of the transfer of this response.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Most of the header fields are optional but some are mandatory.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] When header `Content-Length` is missing from a response with a body, then this should be considered an error in HTTP/1.0 but it may not be an error in HTTP/1.1 if header `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` is present.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Chunked transfer encoding uses a chunk size of 0 to mark the end of the content.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Some old implementations of HTTP/1.0 omitted the header `Content-Length` when the length of the body was not known at the beginning of the response and so the transfer of data to client continued until server closed the socket.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] `Content-Encoding: gzip` informs the client that the body is compressed per the gzip algorithm.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] A content delivery protocol that was displaced by HTTP in the early 1990s.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] A Gopher-inspired protocol which mandates privacy-related features.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Tim Berners-Lee and his team at CERN are credited with inventing HTTP, along with HTML and the associated technology for a web server and a client user interface called web browser.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Berners-Lee designed HTTP in order to help with the adoption of his other idea: the "WorldWideWeb" project, which was first proposed in 1989, now known as the World Wide Web.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Development of HTTP was initiated in 1989 and summarized in a simple document describing the behavior of a client and a server using the first HTTP version, named 0.9.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] That version was subsequently developed, eventually becoming the public 1.0.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Development of early HTTP Request for Comments (RFC) documents started a few years later in a coordinated effort by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), with work later moving to the IETF.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The protocol used had only one method, namely GET, which would request a page from a server.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The response from the server was always an HTML page.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Since 1992, a new document was written to specify the evolution of the basic protocol towards its next full version.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] It supported both the simple request method of the 0.9 version and the full GET request that included the client HTTP version.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] This was the first of the many unofficial HTTP/1.0 drafts that preceded the final work on HTTP/1.0.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The HTTP WG planned to revise and publish new versions of the protocol as HTTP/1.0 and HTTP/1.1 within 1995, but, because of the many revisions, that timeline lasted much more than one year.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The HTTP WG planned also to specify a far future version of HTTP called HTTP-NG (HTTP Next Generation) that would have solved all remaining problems, of previous versions, related to performances, low latency responses, etc. but this work started only a few years later and it was never completed.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] In May 1996, RFC 1945 was published as a final HTTP/1.0 revision of what had been used in previous 4 years as a pre-standard HTTP/1.0-draft which was already used by many web browsers and web servers.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] In early 1996 developers started to even include unofficial extensions of the HTTP/1.0 protocol (i.e. keep-alive connections, etc.) into their products by using drafts of the upcoming HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Since early 1996, major web browsers and web server developers also started to implement new features specified by pre-standard HTTP/1.1 drafts specifications.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] End-user adoption of the new versions of browsers and servers was rapid.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] In March 1996, one web hosting company reported that over 40% of browsers in use on the Internet used the new HTTP/1.1 header "Host" to enable virtual hosting, and that by June 1996, 65% of all browsers accessing their servers were pre-standard HTTP/1.1 compliant.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] In January 1997, RFC 2068 was officially released as HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] In June 1999, RFC 2616 was released to include all improvements and updates based on previous (obsolete) HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Resuming the old 1995 plan of previous HTTP Working Group, in 1997 an *HTTP-NG Working Group* was formed to develop a new HTTP protocol named HTTP-NG (HTTP New Generation).
[src:secure-headers/http-header] A few proposals / drafts were produced for the new protocol to use multiplexing of HTTP transactions inside a single TCP/IP connection, but in 1999, the group stopped its activity passing the technical problems to IETF.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] In 2007, the IETF HTTP Working Group (HTTP WG bis or HTTPbis) was restarted firstly to revise and clarify previous HTTP/1.1 specifications and secondly to write and refine future HTTP/2 specifications (named httpbis).
[src:secure-headers/http-header] In 2009, Google announced SPDY – a binary protocol they developed to speed up web traffic between browsers and servers.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] In many tests, using SPDY was indeed faster than using HTTP/1.1.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] SPDY was integrated into Google's Chromium and then into other major web browsers.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] Some of the ideas about multiplexing HTTP streams over a single TCP connection were taken from various sources, including the work of W3C HTTP-NG Working Group.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] In 2012, HTTP Working Group (HTTPbis) announced the need for a new protocol; initially considering aspects of SPDY and eventually deciding to derive the new protocol from SPDY.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] In May 2015, HTTP/2 was published as RFC 7540.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] The protocol was quickly adopted by web browsers already supporting SPDY and more slowly by web servers.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] As of 2022, HTTP/0.9 support has not been officially, completely deprecated and is still present in many web servers and browsers (for server responses only), even if usually disabled.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] It is unclear how long it will take to decommission HTTP/0.9.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] In 2020, the first drafts of HTTP/3 were published and major web browsers and web servers started to adopt it.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] On 6 June 2022, IETF standardized HTTP/3 as RFC 9114.
[src:secure-headers/http-header] In June 2022, RFC documents were published that deprecated many of the previous documents and introducing a few minor changes and a refactoring of HTTP semantics description into a separate document.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] HTTP Headers are a great booster for web security with easy implementation.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Proper HTTP response headers can help prevent security vulnerabilities like Cross-Site Scripting, Clickjacking, Information disclosure and more.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] In this cheat sheet, we will review all security-related HTTP headers, recommended configurations, and reference other sources for complicated headers.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The `X-Frame-Options` HTTP response header can be used to indicate whether or not a browser should be allowed to render a page in a `<frame>`, `<iframe>`, `<embed>` or `<object>`.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Sites can use this to avoid clickjacking attacks, by ensuring that their content is not embedded into other sites.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Content Security Policy (CSP) frame-ancestors directive obsoletes X-Frame-Options for supporting browsers (source).
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] X-Frame-Options header is only useful when the HTTP response where it is included has something to interact with (e.g. links, buttons).
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] If the HTTP response is a redirect or an API returning JSON data, X-Frame-Options does not provide any security.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Use Content Security Policy (CSP) frame-ancestors directive if possible.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Do not allow displaying of the page in a frame.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The HTTP `X-XSS-Protection` response header is a feature of Internet Explorer, Chrome, and Safari that stops pages from loading when they detect reflected cross-site scripting (XSS) attacks.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] WARNING: Even though this header can protect users of older web browsers that don't yet support CSP, in some cases, this header can create XSS vulnerabilities in otherwise safe websites source.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Use a Content Security Policy (CSP) that disables the use of inline JavaScript.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Do not set this header or explicitly turn it off.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Please see Mozilla X-XSS-Protection for details.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The `X-Content-Type-Options` response HTTP header is used by the server to indicate to the browsers that the MIME types advertised in the Content-Type headers should be followed and not guessed.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] This header is used to block browsers' MIME type sniffing, which can transform non-executable MIME types into executable MIME types (MIME Confusion Attacks).
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Set the Content-Type header correctly throughout the site.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The `Referrer-Policy` HTTP header controls how much referrer information (sent via the Referer header) should be included with requests.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Referrer policy has been supported by browsers since 2014.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Today, the default behavior in modern browsers is to no longer send all referrer information (origin, path, and query string) to the same site but to only send the origin to other sites.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] However, since not all users may be using the latest browsers we suggest forcing this behavior by sending this header on all responses.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The `Content-Type` representation header is used to indicate the original media type of the resource (before any content encoding is applied for sending).
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] If not set correctly, the resource (e.g. an image) may be interpreted as HTML, making XSS vulnerabilities possible.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Although it is recommended to always set the `Content-Type` header correctly, it would constitute a vulnerability only if the content is intended to be rendered by the client and the resource is untrusted (provided or modified by a user).
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The `Cache-Control` header defines how responses are cached by browsers and intermediate caches.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] These directives help reduce the risk of sensitive data being stored or exposed through caching, but use `no-store` when storage of sensitive data must be strictly prevented.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The HTTP `Strict-Transport-Security` response header (often abbreviated as HSTS) instructs browsers to only access the website using HTTPS, even if a user attempts to connect over HTTP.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Please check out HTTP Strict Transport Security Cheat Sheet for more information.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The `Expect-CT` header lets sites opt-in to reporting of Certificate Transparency (CT) requirements.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Given that mainstream clients now require CT qualification, the only remaining value is reporting such occurrences to the nominated report-uri value in the header.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The header is now less about enforcement and more about detection/reporting.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Mozilla recommends avoiding it, and removing it from existing code if possible.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Content Security Policy (CSP) is a security feature that is used to specify the origin of content that is allowed to be loaded on a website or in a web application.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] It is an added layer of security that helps to detect and mitigate certain types of attacks, including Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) and data injection attacks.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] These attacks are used for everything from data theft to site defacement to distribution of malware.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Content Security Policy is complex to configure and maintain.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] If you don't use this header, your site is protected by default by the Same Origin Policy (SOP).
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] What this header does is relax this control in specified circumstances.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` is a CORS (cross-origin resource sharing) header.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] This header indicates whether the response it is related to can be shared with requesting code from the given origin.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] In other words, if siteA requests a resource from siteB, siteB should indicate in its `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` header that siteA is allowed to fetch that resource, if not, the access is blocked due to Same Origin Policy (SOP).
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] If you use it, set specific origins instead of `*`.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Check out Access-Control-Allow-Origin for details.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The HTTP `Cross-Origin-Opener-Policy` (COOP) response header allows you to ensure a top-level document does not share a browsing context group with cross-origin documents.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] This header works together with Cross-Origin-Embedder-Policy (COEP) and Cross-Origin-Resource-Policy (CORP) explained below.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] This mechanism protects against attacks like Spectre which can cross the security boundary established by Same Origin Policy (SOP) for resources in the same browsing context group.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] As these headers are very related to browsers, it may not make sense to be applied to REST APIs or clients that are not browsers.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Isolates the browsing context exclusively to same-origin documents.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The HTTP `Cross-Origin-Embedder-Policy` (COEP) response header prevents a document from loading any cross-origin resources that don't explicitly grant the document permission (using CORP or CORS).
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] A document can only load resources from the same origin, or resources explicitly marked as loadable from another origin.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The `Cross-Origin-Resource-Policy` (CORP) header allows you to control the set of origins that are empowered to include a resource.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] It is a robust defense against attacks like Spectre, as it allows browsers to block a given response before it enters an attacker's process.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Limit current resource loading to the site and sub-domains only.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Permissions-Policy allows you to control which origins can use which browser features, both in the top-level page and in embedded frames.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] For every feature controlled by Feature Policy, the feature is only enabled in the current document or frame if its origin matches the allowed list of origins.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] This means that you can configure your site to never allow the camera or microphone to be activated.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] This prevents that an injection, for example an XSS, enables the camera, the microphone, or other browser feature.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] FLoC is a method proposed by Google in 2021 to deliver interest-based advertisements to groups of users ("cohorts").
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The Electronic Frontier Foundation, Mozilla, and others believe FLoC does not do enough to protect users' privacy.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] A site can declare that it does not want to be included in the user's list of sites for cohort calculation by sending this HTTP header.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The `Server` header describes the software used by the origin server that handled the request — that is, the server that generated the response.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] This is not a security header, but how it is used is relevant for security.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Remove this header or set non-informative values.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The `X-Powered-By` header describes the technologies used by the webserver.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] This information exposes the server to attackers.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Using the information in this header, attackers can find vulnerabilities easier.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Provides information about the .NET version.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Add the following line in your `web.config` in the `<system.web>` section to remove it.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] To remove the `X-AspNetMvc-Version` header, add the below line in `Global.asax` file.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The HTTP `X-Robots-Tag` response header controls how search engines and other automated crawlers index and display resources such as PDFs, images, and other non-HTML content.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] It functions similarly to the `<meta name="robots">` tag, but is applied via the HTTP response header, allowing greater flexibility (e.g., for non-HTML files or server-wide rules).
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] You can also use other directives such as `noarchive`, `nosnippet`, or `noimageindex` depending on your needs.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Server configuration can apply this header selectively — for example, only on specific file types (like PDFs or images).
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The `X-DNS-Prefetch-Control` HTTP response header controls DNS prefetching, a feature by which browsers proactively perform domain name resolution on both links that the user may choose to follow as well as URLs for items referenced by the document, including images, CSS, JavaScript, and so forth.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The default behavior of browsers is to perform DNS caching which is good for most websites.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] If you do not control links on your website, you might want to set `off` as a value to disable DNS prefetch to avoid leaking information to those domains.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The HTTP `Public-Key-Pins` response header was used to associate a specific cryptographic public key with a web server to mitigate MITM attacks with forged certificates.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] It was removed from Chromium in 2018 and is unsupported by all modern browsers.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Remove any `Public-Key-Pins` or `Public-Key-Pins-Report-Only` headers from production.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Rely on Certificate Transparency (CT) and CAA DNS records, which provide superior compromise detection without the operational brittleness of pinning.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] When serving user-provided files, proper HTTP headers should be used to prevent unintended execution in the browser.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] These headers help reduce risks such as Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) and unintended file execution.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The sample code below sets the `X-Frame-Options` header in PHP.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Below is an `.htaccess` sample configuration which sets the `X-Frame-Options` header in Apache.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] As described in the Apache documentation, `Header set` (default `onsuccess`) and `Header always set` operate on separate internal header tables.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] In some cases, both header tables may be used, which can result in duplicate headers if the same header is configured in both contexts.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] If a header needs to be removed entirely, it should be unset in both contexts (`onsuccess` and `always`).
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Add configurations below to your `Web.config` in IIS to send the `X-Frame-Options` header.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Add the line below to your front-end, listen, or backend configurations to send the `X-Frame-Options` header.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Below is a sample configuration, it sets the `X-Frame-Options` header in Nginx.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Note that without the `always` option, the header will only be sent for certain status codes, as described in the nginx documentation.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] You can use helmet to setup HTTP headers in Express.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The code below is a sample for adding the `X-Frame-Options` header.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The Mozilla Observatory is an online tool which helps you to check your website's header status.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] SmartScanner has a dedicated test profile for testing security of HTTP headers.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Online tools usually test the homepage of the given address.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] But SmartScanner scans the whole website.
[src:secure-headers/http-headers-cheat-sheet] So, you can make sure all of your web pages have the right HTTP Headers in place.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] In HTTP, "**Referer**" (a misspelling of "**Referrer**") is an optional HTTP header field that identifies the address of the web page (i.e., the URI or IRI) from which the resource has been requested.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] By checking the referrer, the server providing the new web page can see where the request originated.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] Web sites and web servers log the content of the received Referer field to identify the web page from which the user followed a link, for promotional or statistical purposes.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] This entails a loss of privacy for the user and may introduce a security risk.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] To mitigate security risks, browsers have been steadily reducing the amount of information sent in Referer.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] As of March 2021, by default Chrome, Chromium-based Edge, Firefox, Safari default to sending only the origin in cross-origin requests, stripping out everything but the domain name.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] The misspelling of *referrer* was introduced in the original proposal by computer scientist Phillip Hallam-Baker to incorporate the "Referer" header field into the HTTP specification.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] "Referer" has since become a widely used spelling in the industry when discussing HTTP referrers; usage of the misspelling is not universal, though, as the correct spelling "referrer" is used in some web specifications such as the `Referrer-Policy` HTTP header or the Document Object Model.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] When visiting a web page, the referrer or referring page is the URL of the previous web page from which a link was followed.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] More generally, a referrer is the URL of a previous item which led to this request.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] For example, the referrer for an image is generally the HTML page on which it is to be displayed.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] The referrer field is an optional part of the HTTP request sent by the web browser to the web server.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] Many websites log referrers as part of their attempt to track their users.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] Most web log analysis software can process this information.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] Because referrer information can violate privacy, some web browsers allow the user to disable the sending of referrer information.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] Some proxy and firewall software will also filter out referrer information, to avoid leaking the location of non-public websites.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] This can, in turn, cause problems: some web servers block parts of their website to web browsers that do not send the right referrer information, in an attempt to prevent deep linking or unauthorised use of images (bandwidth theft).
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] Some proxy software has the ability to give the top-level address of the target website as the referrer, which reduces these problems but can still in some cases divulge the user's last-visited web page.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] Many blogs publish referrer information in order to link back to people who are linking to them, and hence broaden the conversation.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] This has led, in turn, to the rise of referrer spam: the sending of fake referrer information in order to popularize the spammer's website.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] It is possible to access the referrer information on the client side using document.referrer in JavaScript.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] This can be used, for example, to individualize a web page based on a user's search engine query.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] However, the referrer field does not always include search keywords, such as when using Google Search with HTTPS.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] Most web servers maintain logs of all traffic, and record the HTTP referrer sent by the web browser for each request.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] This raises a number of privacy concerns, and as a result, a number of systems to prevent web servers being sent the real referring URL have been developed.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] These systems work either by blanking the referrer field or by replacing it with inaccurate data.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] Generally, Internet-security suites blank the referrer data, while web-based servers replace it with a false URL, usually their own.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] This raises the problem of referrer spam.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] The technical details of both methods are fairly consistent – software applications act as a proxy server and manipulate the HTTP request, while web-based methods load websites within frames, causing the web browser to send a referrer URL of their website address.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] Some web browsers give their users the option to turn off referrer fields in the request header.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] Most web browsers do not send the referrer field when they are instructed to redirect using the "Refresh" field.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] This does not include some versions of Opera and many mobile web browsers.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] However, this method of redirection is discouraged by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C).
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] If a website is accessed from a HTTP Secure (HTTPS) connection and a link points to anywhere except another secure location, then the referrer field is not sent.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] The HTML5 standard added support for the attribute/value `rel="noreferrer"`, which instructs the user agent to not send a referrer.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] Another referrer hiding method is to convert the original link URL to a Data URI scheme-based URL containing small HTML page with a meta refresh to the original URL.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] When the user is redirected from the `data:` page, the original referrer is hidden.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] Content Security Policy standard version 1.1 introduced a new *referrer* directive that allows more control over the browser's behaviour in regards to the referrer header.
[src:secure-headers/http-referer] Specifically it allows the webmaster to instruct the browser not to block referrer at all, reveal it only when moving with the same origin etc.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] This article lists standard and notable non-standard HTTP header fields.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] A core set of fields is standardized by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) in RFC 9110 and 9111.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] The Field Names, Header Fields and Repository of Provisional Registrations are maintained by the IANA.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Additional fields may be defined by a web application.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] In the past, non-standard header field names were prefixed with `X-` but this convention was deprecated in June 2012 because of the inconveniences it caused when non-standard fields became standard.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] An earlier restriction on use of `Downgraded-` was lifted in March 2013.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] A few field values can contain comments (i.e. in User-Agent, Server, Via fields), which can be ignored by software.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Many field values may contain a quality (*q*) key-value pair separated by equals sign, specifying a weight to use in content negotiation.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] This section lists header fields used in a request.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 3229, permanent] Acceptable instance-manipulations for the request.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] Media type(s) that is/are acceptable for the response.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] Character sets that are acceptable.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 7089, provisional] Acceptable version in time.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] List of acceptable encodings.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] List of acceptable human languages for response.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [permanent] Initiates a request for cross-origin resource sharing with Origin (below).
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] Authentication credentials for HTTP authentication.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9111, permanent] Used to specify directives that *must* be obeyed by all caching mechanisms along the request-response chain.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Per HTTP/1.1, the `no-cache` value allows the browser to tell the server and intermediate caches that it wants a fresh version of the resource.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] The HTTP/1.0, `Pragma: no-cache` header field has the same purpose.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] The behavior of `Pragma: no-cache` in a *response* is not specified yet some user agents support it.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] HTTP/1.1 specifically warns against relying on this behavior.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] Control options for the current connection and list of hop-by-hop request fields.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9530, Digest Fields] Content-Digest header enables verification of message content integrity by computing a digest over the literal bytes transmitted in the HTTP message.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] This digest reflects the content after applying transformations like Content-Encoding, matching exactly what travels across the network.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] The type of encoding used on the data.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] The length of the request body in octets (8-bit bytes).
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 1544, 1864, 4021, obsolete] A Base64-encoded binary MD5 sum of the content of the request body.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] The Media type of the body of the request (used with POST and PUT requests).
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 2965, 6265, permanent] An HTTP cookie previously sent by the server with `Set-Cookie` (below).
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] The date and time at which the message was originated (in "HTTP-date" format as defined by RFC 9110: HTTP Semantics, section 5.6.7 "Date/Time Formats").
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] Indicates that particular server behaviors are required by the client.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 7239, permanent] Disclose original information of a client connecting to a web server through an HTTP proxy.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] The email address of the user making the request.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, 9113, permanent] The domain name of the server (for virtual hosting), and the TCP port number on which the server is listening.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] The port number may be omitted if the port is the standard port for the service requested.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] If the request is generated directly in HTTP/2, it should not be used.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 7540, 9113, obsolete] A request that upgrades from HTTP/1.1 to HTTP/2 MUST include exactly one `HTTP2-Settings` header field.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] The `HTTP2-Settings` header field is a connection-specific header field that includes parameters that govern the HTTP/2 connection, provided in anticipation of the server accepting the request to upgrade.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] Only perform the action if the client supplied entity matches the same entity on the server.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] This is mainly for methods like PUT to only update a resource if it has not been modified since the user last updated it.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] Allows a *304 Not Modified* to be returned if content is unchanged.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] Allows a *304 Not Modified* to be returned if content is unchanged, see HTTP ETag.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] If the entity is unchanged, send me the part(s) that I am missing; otherwise, send me the entire new entity.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] Only send the response if the entity has not been modified since a specific time.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] Limit the number of times the message can be forwarded through proxies or gateways.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 6454, permanent] Initiates a request for cross-origin resource sharing (asks server for Access-Control-* response fields).
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9111, outdated] Implementation-specific fields that may have various effects anywhere along the request-response chain.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 7240, permanent] Allows client to request that certain behaviors be employed by a server while processing a request.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] Authorization credentials for connecting to a proxy.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] Request only part of an entity.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] The address of the previous web page from which a link to the currently requested page was followed.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Although the intended term is actually spelled "referrer", the misspelling is in the RFC as well as in most implementations, and is therefore considered correct terminology.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] The Trailer general field value indicates that the given set of header fields is present in the trailer of a message encoded with chunked transfer coding.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] The form of encoding used to safely transfer the entity to the user.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Currently defined methods are: chunked, compress, deflate, gzip, identity.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] The user agent string of the user agent.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] Ask the server to upgrade to another protocol.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] Informs the server of proxies through which the request was sent.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 7234, 9111, obsolete] A warning about a possible problem with the entity body.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Since this header is often neither sent by servers nor acknowledged by clients, this header and its codes were obsoleted by the HTTP Working Group in 2022 with RFC 9111.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] The following caching related warning codes were specified under RFC 7234.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] The response provided by a cache is stale (the content's age exceeds a maximum age set by a Cache-Control header or heuristically chosen lifetime).
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] The cache was unable to validate the response, due to an inability to reach the origin server.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] The cache is intentionally disconnected from the rest of the network.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] The cache heuristically chose a freshness lifetime greater than 24 hours and the response's age is greater than 24 hours.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] The warning text may be logged or presented to the user.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Added by a proxy if it applies any transformation to the representation, such as changing the content encoding, media type or the like.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Same as 199, but indicating a persistent warning.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Mainly used to identify Ajax requests (most JavaScript frameworks send this field with value of `XMLHttpRequest`); this also identifies Android apps using WebView.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Requests a web application to disable their tracking of a user.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] This is Mozilla's version of the X-Do-Not-Track header field (since Firefox 4.0 Beta 11).
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Safari and IE9 also have support for this field.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] On March 7, 2011, a draft proposal was submitted to IETF.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] The W3C Tracking Protection Working Group is producing a specification.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] A *de facto* standard for identifying the originating IP address of a client connecting to a web server through an HTTP proxy or load balancer.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] A *de facto* standard for identifying the original host requested by the client in the `Host` HTTP request header, since the host name and/or port of the reverse proxy (load balancer) may differ from the origin server handling the request.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] A *de facto* standard for identifying the originating protocol of an HTTP request, since a reverse proxy (or a load balancer) may communicate with a web server using HTTP even if the request to the reverse proxy is HTTPS.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] An alternative form of the header (X-ProxyUser-Ip) is used by Google clients talking to Google servers.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Non-standard header field used by Microsoft applications and load-balancers.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Requests a web application to override the method specified in the request (typically POST) with the method given in the header field (typically PUT or DELETE).
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] This can be used when a user agent or firewall prevents PUT or DELETE methods from being sent directly (this is either a bug in the software component, which ought to be fixed, or an intentional configuration, in which case bypassing it may be the wrong thing to do).
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Allows easier parsing of the MakeModel/Firmware that is usually found in the User-Agent String of AT&T Devices.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Links to an XML file on the Internet with a full description and details about the device currently connecting.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] In the example to the right is an XML file for an AT&T Samsung Galaxy S2.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Implemented as a misunderstanding of the HTTP specifications.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Common because of mistakes in implementations of early HTTP versions.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Has exactly the same functionality as standard Connection field.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Server-side deep packet inspection of a unique ID identifying customers of Verizon Wireless; also known as "perma-cookie" or "supercookie".
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Used to prevent cross-site request forgery.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Alternative header names are: `X-CSRFToken` and `X-XSRF-TOKEN`.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Correlates HTTP requests between a client and server.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] The Save-Data client hint request header available in Chrome, Opera, and Yandex browsers lets developers deliver lighter, faster applications to users who opt-in to data saving mode in their browser.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] The Sec-GPC (Global Privacy Control) request header indicates whether the user consents to a website or service selling or sharing their personal information with third parties.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] This section lists header fields used in a response.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 8942, experimental] Requests HTTP Client Hints.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 7480, permanent] Specifying which web sites can participate in cross-origin resource sharing.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 5789, permanent] Specifies which patch document formats this server supports.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] What partial content range types this server supports via byte serving.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9111, permanent] The age the object has been in a proxy cache in seconds.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] Valid methods for a specified resource.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] To be used for a *405 Method not allowed*.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 7838, permanent] A server uses "Alt-Svc" header (meaning Alternative Services) to indicate that its resources can also be accessed at a different network location (host or port) or using a different protocol.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] When using HTTP/2, servers should instead send an ALTSVC frame.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9111, permanent] Tells all caching mechanisms from server to client whether they may cache the response.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] If a web server responds with `Cache-Control: no-cache`, then a web browser or other caching system (intermediate proxies) must not use the response to satisfy subsequent requests without first checking with the originating server (this process is called validation).
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] This header field is part of HTTP/1.1, and is ignored by some caches and browsers.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] It may be simulated by setting the `Expires` HTTP/1.0 header field value to a time earlier than the response time.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Notice that `no-cache` is not instructing the browser or proxies about whether or not to cache the content.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] It tells the browser and proxies to validate the cache content with the server before using it (this is done via `If-Modified-Since`, `If-Unmodified-Since`, `If-Match`, and `If-None-Match`).
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Sending a `no-cache` value thus instructs a browser or proxy to not use the cache contents merely based on "freshness criteria" of the cache content.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Another common way to prevent old content from being shown to the user without validation is `Cache-Control: max-age=0` which instructs the user agent that the content is stale and should be validated before use.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] The value `no-store` instructs a browser to *not* cache the response, yet the browser is allowed to cache it none-the-less.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] In particular, the HTTP/1.1 definition draws a distinction between history stores and caches.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] If the user navigates back to a previous page, a browser may show a page that was stored on disk in the history store.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] This is correct behavior according to the specification.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Many user agents provide different behavior in loading pages from the history store or cache depending on whether the protocol is HTTP or HTTPS.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] Control options for the current connection and list of hop-by-hop response fields.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 2616, 4021, 6266, permanent] An opportunity to raise a "File Download" dialogue box for a known MIME type with binary format or suggest a filename for dynamic content.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Quotes are necessary with special characters.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] The natural language or languages of the intended audience for the enclosed content.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] The length of the response body in octets (8-bit bytes).
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] An alternate location for the returned data.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 1544, 1864, 4021, obsolete] A Base64-encoded binary MD5 sum of the content of the response.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] Where in a full body message this partial message belongs.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] The MIME type of this content.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] The date and time that the message was sent (in "HTTP-date" format as defined by RFC 9110).
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 3229, permanent] Specifies the delta-encoding entity tag of the response.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] An identifier for a specific version of a resource, often a message digest.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9111, permanent] Gives the date/time after which the response is considered stale (in "HTTP-date" format as defined by RFC 9110).
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 3229, permanent] Instance-manipulations applied to the response.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] The last modified date for the requested object (in "HTTP-date" format as defined by RFC 9110).
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 8288, permanent] Used to express a typed relationship with another resource, where the relation type is defined by RFC 8288.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] Used in redirection, or when a new resource has been created.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 2626, permanent] This field is supposed to set P3P policy, in the form of `P3P:CP="your_compact_policy"`.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] However, P3P did not take off, most browsers have never fully implemented it; a lot of websites set this field with fake policy text, enough to fool browsers into thinking a P3P policy existed and granting permissions for third party cookies.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] For example: `P3P: CP="This is not a P3P policy!
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9111, permanent] Implementation-specific fields that may have various effects anywhere along the request-response chain.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 7240, permanent] Indicates which Prefer tokens were honored by the server and applied to the processing of the request.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] Request authentication to access the proxy.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 7469, permanent] HTTP Public Key Pinning, announces hash of website's authentic TLS certificate.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] If an entity is temporarily unavailable, this instructs the client to try again later.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Value could be a specified period of time (in seconds) or a HTTP-date.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] A name for the server.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 6797, permanent] A HSTS Policy informing the HTTP client how long to cache the HTTPS-only policy and whether this applies to subdomains.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 2295, permanent] Tracking Status header, value suggested to be sent in response to a DNT (do-not-track) request.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] Ask the client to upgrade to another protocol.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] Tells downstream proxies how to match future request headers to decide whether the cached response can be used rather than requesting a fresh one from the origin server.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] Informs the client of proxies through which the response was sent.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 7234, RFC 9111, obsolete] A general warning about possible problems with the entity body.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 9110, permanent] Indicates the authentication scheme that should be used to access the requested entity.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] [RFC 7034, obsolete] Clickjacking protection: `deny` - no rendering within a frame, `sameorigin` - no rendering if origin mismatch, `allow-from` - allow from specified location, `allowall` - non-standard, allow from any location.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Notify to prefer to enforce Certificate Transparency.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Used to configure network request logging.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] To allow or disable different features or APIs of the browser.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Tells the browser to refresh the page or redirect to a different URL, either after a given number of seconds (`0` meaning immediately), or when a new resource has been created.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Introduced by Netscape in 1995 and has since become a de facto standard supported by most web browsers.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Was eventually standardized in the HTML Living Standard in 2017.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Instructs the user agent to store reporting endpoints for an origin.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] CGI header field specifying the status of the HTTP response.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Normal HTTP responses use a separate "Status-Line" instead, defined by RFC 9110.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] The `Timing-Allow-Origin` response header specifies origins that are allowed to see values of attributes retrieved via features of the Resource Timing API, which would otherwise be reported as zero due to cross-origin restrictions.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Provide the duration of the audio or video in seconds.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Not supported by current browsers – the header was only supported by Gecko browsers, from which support was removed in 2015.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] The only defined value, "nosniff", prevents Internet Explorer from MIME-sniffing a response away from the declared content-type.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] This also applies to Google Chrome, when downloading extensions.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] ASP.NET, PHP, JBoss) supporting the web application (version details are often in `X-Runtime`, `X-Version`, or `X-AspNet-Version`).
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Specifies the component that is responsible for a particular redirect.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Recommends the preferred rendering engine (often a backward-compatibility mode) to use to display the content.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] Also used to activate Chrome Frame in Internet Explorer.
[src:secure-headers/list-of-http-header-fields] In HTML Standard, only the `IE=edge` value is defined.
